-- In java every single class you write automatically inherits
from a "Grandparent" class called Object.

that means if class is empty, it already has several methods 'built-in'.

-- toString(), equals(),hashcode().

1. toString(): The "Description" Method
-- so if you print an object java prints the class name + Memory Address
We override this to human-readable summary.

-- Default: ClassName@HexAddress
-- Overridden: "Student[Name=Aryan, ID=101]"

2. equals(Object obj): The "Logic" Check
-- == checks that if two variables have exact same spot in memory or not.
-- .equals() is designed to checks if two difference objects contains the same
data or not.(logic: It compares Content, not Container.)

3. hashcode(): The "ID Number"
-- it return the integer acts as a "digital fingerprint" for the object.
It is used by collections like HashMap() or HashSet() to find objects quickly.

